==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Poverty
<hw>Pov"er*ty</hw> <pr>(p⟦ocr⟧v"⟦etil⟧r*t⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[OE. <ets>poverte</ets>, OF. <ets>povert⟦eacute⟧</ets>, F.
<ets>pauvret⟦eacute⟧</ets>, fr. L. <ets>paupertas</ets>, fr.
<ets>pauper</ets> poor. See <er>Poor</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
quality or state of being poor or indigent; want or scarcity of means of
subsistence; indigence; need.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Swathed in numblest
<xex>poverty</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Keble.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The drunkard and the glutton shall come to <qex>poverty</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Prov. xxiii. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any deficiency of elements or resources that are
needed or desired, or that constitute richness; <as>as, <ex>poverty</ex>
of soil; <ex>poverty</ex> of the blood; <ex>poverty</ex> of
ideas.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Poverty grass</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a name
given to several slender grasses (as <spn>Aristida dichotoma</spn>, and
<spn>Danthonia spicata</spn>) which often spring up on old and worn-out
fields.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Indigence; penury; beggary; need; lack; want;
scantiness; sparingness; meagerness; jejuneness.</syn> <usage>
<er>Poverty</er>, <er>Indigence</er>, <er>Pauperism</er>.
<xex>Poverty</xex> is a relative term; what is <xex>poverty</xex> to a
monarch, would be competence for a day laborer. <xex>Indigence</xex>
implies extreme distress, and almost absolute destitution.
<xex>Pauperism</xex> denotes entire dependence upon public charity, and,
therefore, often a hopeless and degraded state.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Powen</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Powan</ent>⟦br⟧
